<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06325133 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06325133 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  AUTO; MOVIE; FACILITY; ...; CHANGE; CONSTRUCTION; SAN-JOSE; CITY; COUNCIL;AGREEMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The San Jose City Council unanimously approved plans Tuesday night for a new16-screen movie house on Capitol Expressway that pleased the theater developerbut disturbed operators of a flea market that shares the lot.;    CouncilmanGeorge Shirakawa, saying that it's time South San Jose gets &quot;amenities&quot; likethe theater complex, disappointed the Capitol Flea Market crowd with his standin favor of Syufy Enterprises.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  CAPITOL DRIVE-IN TO BE INDOOR COMPLEX  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT (publ. 11/21/91, pg. 2A);  Headlines in Wednesdayafternoon's Mercury News incorrectly reported that a new indoor theatercomplex will replace the Capitol Drive-In in South San Jose. The movie houseand drive- in will share the site.  </MEMO><TEXT>     But Mayor Susan Hammer and the nine other council members sided withShirakawa, whose District 7 encompasses the area.;    The city staff and Syufybacked a plan for 885 vending stalls and 1,803 parking spaces on the lot --now site of the Capitol Drive-In -- plus a requirement that Sunday matineesstart after 2 p.m.;    But Jason Garner, a flea market spokesman, said therewouldn't be enough parking spaces to handle both the flea market and thematinees during peak hours.;    Garner also said that at least 45 flea marketvendors would lose their stalls under the plan.;    Councilwoman Pat Sausedo,who voted for the theater, said: &quot;Nothing has been given on the part of Syufy.That causes me some concern.&quot;;    Syufy officials standing outside the councilchambers brusquely dismissed questions regarding compromise.;    &quot;We have nocomment,&quot; said Jack Myhill, Syufy general manager. &quot;We're happy with theoutcome.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  NICK ANDERSON, Mercury News Staff Writer  <